    allergen_flags: { contains_dairy: true, contains_eggs: true, contains_fish: false, contains_shellfish: false, contains_nuts: false, contains_peanuts: false, contains_wheat: false, contains_soy: false, contains_sesame: false },
    ingredients: ["10 eggs, whole, cracked", "1 cup egg whites", "1/3 cup milk, full fat or cream", "1 tablespoon coconut oil", "1.5 teaspoon caraway seeds", "1 teaspoon of both kosher salt and black pepper", "4 favorite sausage link, sliced into half-moons", "1 Avocado, quartered, sliced lengthwise", "1 tablespoon ricotta cheese, crumbled"],
    instructions: ["Preheat oven to 375 F. Crack eggs directly into a blender or bowl (crack eggs into a bowl if you are using an immersion blender. Otherwise do this in the blender). Add the egg whites, milk, coconut oil, and season with salt, pepper, and caraway seeds. Blend for 10-20 seconds, avoiding over blending, until all ingredients are emulsified as one.", "Liberally spray the bottom of the sheet pan with spray oil. Add foil on top, covering the entire length and width of the pan, and spray liberally a second time. Slice the sausage links into half-moons and keep them aside in a bowl until needed (though the image shows parchment paper, upon testing the recipe, I realized foil was a better lining product than parchment, due to its ability to stick to the pan uniformly). Pour the egg mix into the pan carefully. Add the sliced sausages by spreading around the pan as evenly as possible. Transfer the pan carefully into the middle rack oven and bake for 30 minutes. Rotate the pan 180 degrees halfway (after 15 minutes) through the baking period - this will allow even cooking.  Set a timer.", "After 30 minutes, test the eggs by sticking a fork, toothpick, or cake tester into the middle of the pan and removing it. If eggs are fully set and none stick to your poking tool of choice, the sheet pan eggs are done. Otherwise, add 2-4 minutes at a time. Remove from the oven and cool on the side (set the pan on top of oven mitts or cooling racks to avoid cracking/burning the surface of your countertop). Once cooled down, cut into even squares. The recipe makes 8 - 6.5oz/188g squares. Transfer to a deep Tupperware container and store in the fridge. "],
